'''Amiya Prosad Sen''' (born 1952) is a historian with an interest in the intellectual and cultural history of modern India.<ref>{{cite book|title=Issues in modern Indian history: for Sumit Sarkar|editor=Biswamoy Pati|publisher=Popular Prakashan|year=2000|page=344|chapter=Notes on contributors|isbn=978-81-7154-658-9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S2Yn4LlujqsC&pg=PA344}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=  Pathak|first=Avijit|year=2001|title=Book reviews and notices|journal=Contributions to Indian Sociology|publisher=Sage  |volume=35|issue=2|pages= 287–288|url=http://cis.sagepub.com/cgi/pdf_extract/35/2/287|doi=10.1177/006996670103500217}}</ref> Currently he is Sivadasani Fellow at the Oxford Centre for Hindu Studies, Oxford  (UK). He was previously the Heinrich Zimmer Chair at the South Asia Institute, [[Heidelberg University]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Zimmer Chair - Amiya P. Sen|url=http://www.sai.uni-heidelberg.de/en/zimmer-chair/sen.php|accessdate=13 October 2014}}</ref> He has served as Professor of Modern Indian History at [[Jamia Millia Islamia]], New Delhi. He has been Agatha Harrison Fellow to the [[University of Oxford]]<ref>[http://www.ox.ac.uk/gazette/backissues/9394/071093  Gazette 7 October 1993; No. 4301; Vol. 124] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071004215232/http://www.ox.ac.uk/gazette/backissues/9394/071093 |date=4 October 2007 }}</ref> and [[visiting professor|Visiting Fellow]] to the [[Indian Institute of Advanced Study]], Shimla,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iias.org/old_academics_fellows_of_the_institute3.html |title=Academic Life |publisher=IIAS |accessdate=16 January 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090621115927/http://www.iias.org/old_academics_fellows_of_the_institute3.html |archivedate=21 June 2009 }}</ref> and the Centre for Contemporary Studies, [[Nehru Memorial Museum & Library]], New Delhi. During 2007–08, he was Tagore professor at [[Vishwa Bharati]], [[Shantiniketan]].

Sen took his bachelor's and master's degrees in history from [[St. Stephen's College, Delhi]] and also pursued his PhD there. After a brief career in [[Indian Civil Services]], he took up teaching and research in 1984.<ref>{{Harvnb|Sen|2001}}</ref>

